ms]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American robot films]]\n[[Category:American animated science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's drama films]]\n[[Category:Animated drama films]]\n[[Category:Animated buddy films]]\n[[Category:Animated films based on manhua]]\n[[Category:Animated films about robots]]\n[[Category:Chinese action adventure films]]\n[[Category:Chinese animated films]]\n[[Category:Chinese films]]\n[[Category:Chinese children's films]]\n[[Category:Chinese animated science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the future]]\n[[Category:Netflix Animation films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about friendship]]\n[[Category:Films based on Internet-based works]]\n[[Category:2010s buddy comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:Anime-influenced Western animation]]\n", "name_user": "121.7.139.245", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Next_Gen_(film)"}
{"title_page": "The Red Line (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|American television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = The Red Line\n| image =\n| caption =\n| genre = [[Drama (genre)|Drama]]\n| creator = {{Plain list|\n*[[Caitlin Parrish]]\n*Erica Weiss\n}}\n| starring = {{Plain list|\n*[[Noah Wyle]]\n*[[Noel Fisher]]\n*[[Michael Patrick Thornton]]\n*Aliyah Royale\n*Vinny Chhibber\n*[[Emayatzy Corinealdi]]\n*[[Howard Charles]]\n}}\n| composer = {{Plain list|\n*Blake Neely\n*Sherri Chung\n}}\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| num_seasons = 1\n| num_episodes = 8\n| list_episodes =\n| executive_producer = {{Plain list|\n*Caitlin Parrish\n*Erica Weiss\n*Sunil Nayar\n*[[Ava DuVernay]]\n*[[Greg Berlanti]]\n*Sarah Schechter\n}}\n| producer =\n| cinematography =\n| editor =\n| camera =\n| runtime = 42 minutes\n| company = {{Plain list|\n*[[Greg Berlanti|Berlanti Productions]]\n*Array Filmworks\n*Foward Movement\n*[[CBS Television Studios]]\n*[[Warner Bros. Television]]\n}}\n| distributor = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| network = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format = [[1080i]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| audio_format =\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2019|4|28}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2019|5|19}}\n| website = https://www.cbs.com/shows/the-red-line/\n| website_title = Official website\n}}\n\n'''''The Red Line''''' is an eight-episode American [[Drama (genre)|drama]] [[Television show#Miniseries, limited series, and event series|limited television series]] created and written by [[Caitlin Parrish]] and Erica Weiss premiered on [[CBS]] on April 28 and concluded on May 19, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=The TVLine-Up: What's Leaving, New and Returning the Week of May 19|url=https://tvline.com/2019/05/18/tv-schedule-what-to-watch-kids-are-alright-cancelled/|work=[[TVLine]]|date=May 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt stars [[Noah Wyle]], [[Emayatzy Corinealdi]], Aliyah Royale, [[Noel Fisher]], [[Michael Patrick Thornton]], Vinny Chhibber, [[Howard Charles]] and Elizabeth Laidlaw. The title refers to [[Red_Line_(CTA)|a rapid transit line]] in [[Chicago, Illinois]] run by the [[Chicago Transit Authority|Chicago Transit Authority (CTA)]] as part of the city's \"L\" system.\n\n== Plot ==\n''The Red Line''{{'}}s plot involves a white cop in [[Chicago]] who mistakenly shoots and kills a black doctor. It follows three different families with connections to the case: the victim's husband and their adopted daughter; the daughter's birth mother, who is running for city council, who is married with a young son; and the policeman, whose brother is a paraplegic ex-cop and whose father is a retired police captain.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Noah Wyle]] as Daniel Calder, a high school teacher whose husband, Harrison Brennan, is mistakenly shot by a [[Chicago Police Department]] (CPD) officer\n*[[Noel Fisher]] as CPD Officer Paul Evans\n*[[Michael Patrick Thornton]] as Jim Evans, Paul's paraplegic brother and former CPD officer\n*Aliyah Royale as Jira Calder-Brennan, Daniel and Harrison's adopted teenaged daughter\n*Vinny Chhibber as Liam, Jira's literature teacher, Daniel's colleague and emerging love interest\n*[[Emayatzy Corinealdi]] as Tia Young, Jira's birth mother, campaigning against the CPD's responsibility for the city's [[Crime in Chicago|nearly 600 annual murders]]\n*[[Howard Charles]] as Ethan Young, Tia's husband, a [[Motorman (locomotive)|motorman]] on the [[Chicago Transit Authority]]\u2019s elevated [[Red Line (CTA)|Red Line]]\n*Elizabeth Laidlaw as Victoria \u201cVic\u201d Renna, Paul's police partner\n*[[Enuka Okuma]] as Suzanne Davis, Tia's sister and campaign manager\n*[[Glynn Turman]] as Nathan Gordon, incumbent alderman and Tia's opponent\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table|background=#FB6464|overall=|title=9 Flying Ship|director=|writer=|airdate=September 27, 2020|airdateR=|viewers=|country=U.S.|prodcode=|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = We Must All Care\n |DirectedBy  