{"title_page": "Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{About|the college football kickoff game|the college football bowl game|Peach Bowl}}\n{{Collegebowl\n| name = Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game\n| full_name =\n| nickname =\n| defunct =\n| logo = File:Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game logo.png\n| image_size =\n| caption = Current logo, used since 2016\n| stadium = [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]]\n| previous_stadiums = [[Georgia Dome]]\n| location = [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]]\n| previous_locations =\n| years = 2008\u2013present\n| previous_tie-ins =\n| conference_tie-ins =\n| payout = 1,900,000 per team\n| sponsors = <center>[[Chick-fil-A]] (2008\u2013present)</center>\n| former_names =\n| prev_matchup_year = 2019\n| prev_matchup_season = 2019\n| prev_matchup_teams = '''No. 2 [[2019 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] 42''', [[2019 Duke Blue Devils football team|Duke]] 3\n| next_matchup_year = 2020\n| next_matchup_season = 2020\n| next_matchup_teams = [[2020 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]] vs. [[2020 West Virginia Mountaineers football team|West Virginia]]\n}}\nThe '''Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game''' is an annual [[college football]] game played on the opening weekend of the [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|NCAA Division I FBS]] season in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. The event coincides with [[Labor Day]] weekend in the United States. From its inception in 2008 until 2016, the game was held in the [[Georgia Dome]]. The Georgia Dome's replacement, [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]], began hosting the game starting in 2017.\n\n== History ==\n\nOrganizers intended for the game to become a national spotlight game, on par with the [[Kickoff Classic]] held in [[Giants Stadium|the Meadowlands]] from 1983\u20132002, and the Disneyland [[Pigskin Classic]] in the 1990s. In 2008, ESPN's ''[[College GameDay (football)|College Gameday]]'' broadcast from [[Downtown Atlanta]], while ESPN corporate sponsors and local Atlanta-based companies featured prominent displays at Fanzones in Atlanta's [[Centennial Olympic Park]].<ref name=\"sportsbusinessjournal.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessjournal.com/article/59825|title='Kickoff' aims for college football spotlight|work=sportsbusinessjournal.com}}</ref>\n\nPayout to each team depends on the amount of revenue gained in excess of the Kickoff's $5.5 million budget. In 2008, Clemson and Alabama were both expected to receive more than $2 million.<ref name=\"sportsbusinessjournal.com\" />\n\n=== Series summary ===\nThe first game, known that year as the Chick-fil-A College Kickoff, was played on August 30, 2008, the opening Saturday of the [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008 season]]. [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] defeated [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]] 34\u201310.\n\nAlabama returned to the Chick-fil-A Kickoff for the 2009 game, defeating [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]] to begin the [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009 season]].\n\n[[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] and [[UCLA Bruins football|UCLA]] were initially slated to play in 2010, but Auburn officials later backed out of the offer. ABC attempted to replace Auburn with [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]], but the switch prompted UCLA to opt out entirely because the game would essentially be a home game for the Atlanta-based Yellow Jackets, with no scheduled return trip to [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.al.com/auburnbeat/2009/04/auburnucla_game_in_2010_nixed.html|title=Auburn-UCLA game in 2010 nixed|work=AL.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bruinsnation.com/2009/4/28/857192/auburn-ad-jay-jacobs-is-under|title=Auburn A.D. (Jay Jacobs) Is Under Intense Criticism For Ducking UCLA|author=Nestor|work=Bruins Nation}}</ref> Finally, an agreement was reached in which [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] and [[North Carolina Tar Heels football|North Carolina]] would match up, with the Tigers winning 30\u201324. The 2010 game also saw the introduction of a trophy awarded to the winner, the Old Leather Helmet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chick-fil-akickoffgame.com/FANCENTRAL/TheOldLeatherHelmet/tabid/152/Default.aspx|title=A College Football Celebration|work=Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140220230834/http://www.chick-fil-akickoffgame.com/FANCENTRAL/TheOldLeatherHelmet/tabid/152/Default.aspx|archivedate=February 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe 2011 edition was the first Chick-fil-A Kickoff to feature a team that was not a member of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] or [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]], the two conferences with tie-ins to the [[Peach Bowl|Chick-fil-A Bowl]]. [[Boise State Broncos football|Boise State]] of the [[Mountain West Conference]], one of the most successful programs from a BCS non-automatic qualifier conference in recent years, defeated [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] 35\u201321.\n\nThe Chick-fil-A Kickoff consisted of two games in 2012. [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] defeated [[NC State Wolfpack football|NC State]] 35\u201321 on Friday night prior to Clemson defeating Auburn 26\u201319 in the headliner on Saturday. The dual-game idea was first mentioned in the ''[[Miami Herald]]'' in May 2010, when Gary Stokan, president of the Chick-Fil-A Bowl, told the newspaper that there was the possibility of having Alabama face [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] in a rematch of the [[1993 Sugar Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/sports_college/2010/05/alabama-vs-miami-to-open-2012-in-atlanta.html|title=College Gridiron 365 \u2013 Football Blog \u2013 Orlando Sentinel|work=orlandosentinel.com|access-date=May 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510163458/http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/sports_college/2010/05/alabama-vs-miami-to-open-2012-in-atlanta.html|archive-date=May 10, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe 2013 edition was a rematch of the 2009 game. Alabama, the two-time defending [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] national champions, once again defeated Virginia Tech, this time by a score of 35\u201310.\n\n2014 would again feature two games. [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]] defeated Boise State 35\u201313 in a Thursday night game. Alabama would defeat [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] 33\u201323 in the headliner on Saturday afternoon. It marked the first ever meeting between Alabama and West Virginia in any sport. \n\nThe 2015 Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game, which moved to [[CBS Sports|CBS]] that season, returned to a single game with the ACC's [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville Cardinals]] taking on the SEC's Auburn Tigers. Auburn defeated Louisville, 31\u201324.\n\nThe 2016 Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game, which moved back to ESPN, featured North Carolina and Georgia, both making their second appearances in the kickoff series. The Bulldogs defeated the Tar Heels 33\u201324 in the final edition of the game played the Georgia Dome.\n\nThe 2017 event was the third doubleheader in the series. Alabama defeated [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]] on Saturday evening by a score of 24\u20137, serving as the ''[[Saturday Night Football]]'' season opener.  Tennessee defeated Georgia Tech 42\u201341 in double overtime on Monday evening.  The two games were the first in the series to be played in the new Mercedes-Benz Stadium in Downtown Atlanta.\n\n==Game results ==\n{| class=wikitable\n! Season !! Date !! colspan=2|Winning team !! colspan=2|Losing team !! Attendance \n|-\n|[[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]]\n| August 30, 2008\n| style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Alabama Crimson Tide}};\"|<small>24</small> '''[[2008 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|<span style=\"color:white;\">Alabama Crimson Tide</span>]]''' || '''34'''\n| style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Clemson Tigers}};\"|<small>9</small> '''[[2008 Clemson Tigers football team|<span st